data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces unhelpful failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest provides dedicated collection and assertion APIs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — shows both values on failure instead of just "false". Note: expected value goes first.
- **Add failure messages** to any `Assert.IsTrue` calls so you know *what* failed.
- **`Assert.IsNotNull()`** instead of `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` when null-checking.
- **Avoid redundant checks** — `AreEqual(3, ...)` already proves count > 0.

**Other useful collection assertions:**

```csharp
// Verify specific elements exist
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// Verify all elements are unique
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);

// Verify collection type contents
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Verify exact contents (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);

// Verify same contents (order-insensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);
```

The general rule: prefer **specific assertions** (`AreEqual`, `IsNotNull`, `CollectionAssert`) over `Assert.IsTrue` — they give much better diagnostics on failure.
